{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Add pinyin — re-introduction under new rendering warrants full gloss",
    "content": "**Add pinyin: use (德, *de*).**\n\nThe reader needs the pinyin here because:\n\n1. The English rendering has changed — \"virtue\" in the block quote is now \"character\" in the analysis. The hanzi 德 alone may not be enough for a reader who doesn't read Chinese to connect the two. The pinyin *de* is the bridge: it appeared with \"virtue (德, *de*)\" in line 34, and now reappears with \"character (德, *de*)\" in line 40. The reader thinks: \"ah, same *de*, different translation — something has shifted.\"\n\n2. This is effectively a *re-introduction* of the term under a new rendering. Our convention (line 8-9 of YAML) gives hanzi + pinyin on first occurrence of each key term. \"Character\" is the first occurrence of 德 *under this rendering*, so it warrants the full gloss.\n\n3. TN3 is attached at exactly this point. The TN uses \"德 (de)\" in its text. Having (德, *de*) in the main text creates consistency with the TN it anchors.\n\nChange line 40 from `\"character\" (德)` to `\"character\" (德, *de*)`."
  }
}
